Despite this high share of marriages with children, only one‐third of them are able to prolong and repair their marital union after a divorce. Hence the rise in alternatives to marriage in the form of living‐together arrangements.
The number of ‘only living‐together couples’ has been increasing since 1975. As almost half of living‐together couples have children, the acceptance of cohabitation‐as‐a‐family model is currently evident and an important dynamic of the family specifically in France, where less than half of the child outcomes from lone parent families are perceived positively (Musard et al., 2011). Otherwise, these living‐together couples usually involve stable partnerships without marriage.
Cases of cohabitation coming before marriage (and sometimes, leading to divorce) and married people constituting living‐together couples have signified that both of these constitute a helpful resource in maintaining stable union‐formation. Instead, the period of marriage has greatly decreased but marriage partners constitute the lynchpin of the families, consequently raise concerns around the marriage process as a ‘pathway to family instability’. Marriage of partners with opposite socioeconomic background has increased the instability within the family dynamics as they create disincentive to work hard because of social security policies.
